<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-05-05T07:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-05-05T07:00:00-05:00" n="285" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d285">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/5264: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-05-05T20:00:00+08:00">May 5, 1930—8
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received May 8—10:40 a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>306. Legation’s 299, May 2, 5 p.m. Under instructions from the Inspector
                            General the Commissioner of Customs at Tientsin on May 3 directed the
                            Customs Bank to turn over to him balance of all customs funds on hand.
                            The bank declined, pleading “force majeure”. The Commissioner of Customs
                            is from today both assessing and collecting customs duties on behalf of
                            the Central Government.</p>
                        <closer>For the Minister:<lb/><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Perkins</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
